Here is the ideal end-to-end journey from the moment the insurance desk person (or doctor) opens your software to the moment a TPA-ready pre-authorization document is generated.

Phase 1: Login & Landing
The user opens Aivana and lands on a dashboard showing:

Active patients currently admitted or in consultation

A prominent "New Pre-Authorization" button

A queue of draft/pending/submitted pre-auths with status badges (Draft, Submitted, Query Raised, Approved, Denied)

Notifications for TPA queries that need response

The insurance desk person clicks "New Pre-Authorization" or selects an existing patient from the active list.

Phase 2: Patient Identification
What happens automatically
If launched from within an active consultation (doctor clicked it), the patient's name, UHID, age, gender, and basic demographics are pre-filled from HIS/EMR.

If launched standalone by insurance desk, a search bar appears: search by UHID, name, phone number, or policy number.

What the user sees
Patient card with photo, name, age, gender, UHID

A prompt: "Does this patient have an active consultation or clinical note?"

Yes → auto-pull clinical data from the doctor's latest session (NEXUS engine output, vitals, DDx, findings)

No → manual entry path (the user will type or paste clinical details)

What gets validated
Patient identity confirmed (name + DOB or UHID match)

System checks if a pre-auth already exists for this patient + this admission (prevents duplicates)

Phase 3: Insurance Card Capture
What happens
The user is prompted: "Scan or photograph the patient's insurance card (front & back)"

Camera opens on mobile; file upload on desktop

OCR runs automatically and extracts: policy number, insurer name, TPA name, TPA ID card number, sum insured, policy validity dates, proposer name, insured name, relationship

What the user sees
Extracted fields shown in an editable form, pre-filled from OCR

Confidence indicators on each field (green = high confidence, yellow = review needed)

Fields the OCR couldn't read are highlighted in red for manual entry

A dropdown for TPA name (MDIndia, MediAssist, Raksha, etc.) auto-selected based on OCR but editable

What gets validated
Policy number format check (basic regex per known insurer patterns)

Policy dates: is the policy currently active? Warning if expired or expiring within 7 days

Sum insured captured for later cost-vs-coverage comparison

Phase 4: Clinical Data Review
Scenario A: Clinical notes exist (doctor used Aivana voice scribe)
The system auto-populates from the NEXUS engine output:

Chief complaints extracted from transcription

Duration of present ailment from conversation context

Relevant clinical findings from doctor's dictation

Vitals (BP, pulse, temp, SpO2, RR) from the session

Provisional diagnosis with ICD-10 code (top DDx from NEXUS)

Severity scores (PhenoIntensity, UrgencyQuotient, DeteriorationVelocity)

Voice-captured test interpretations (e.g., "X-ray shows right lower lobe consolidation")

The user sees all of this in a review screen with everything editable. The treating doctor either reviews it themselves or the insurance desk person confirms with the doctor.

Scenario B: No existing clinical notes
The system shows a structured clinical entry form with:

Chief complaints (free text)

Duration

Nature of illness (Acute / Chronic / Acute on Chronic) dropdown

Clinical findings (free text with smart suggestions)

Diagnosis search (type-ahead with ICD-10 lookup)

Vitals entry fields

A "Use Voice" button that lets the user dictate findings and the AI structures them

What happens in both scenarios
The user selects the primary diagnosis (radio button if multiple DDx exist)

The user selects proposed line of treatment: Medical / Surgical / Intensive Care / Investigation (checkboxes)

If Surgical is checked → surgery name field and route (Open/Lap/Endo/Robotic) appear

If it's an injury → accident details panel expands (date, cause, MLC yes/no, FIR number)

If maternity → gravida/para/LMP/EDD/delivery type fields appear

Phase 5: Past History & Admission Details
What the user fills
Past medical history as checkboxes with "since when" fields: Diabetes, Hypertension, Heart Disease, Asthma/COPD, Epilepsy, Cancer, Kidney Disease, Liver Disease, Alcoholism, Smoking, Others

Previous hospitalization: Yes/No, details, last date

Admission type: Emergency or Planned (radio)

Date and time of admission (auto-filled to current if emergency)

Room category: General Ward / Semi-Private / Private / ICU / ICCU / NICU / HDU

Expected length of stay (days in ward + days in ICU)

Smart behavior
If NEXUS severity is "Critical" or SpO2 < 90%, system auto-suggests ICU and flags it

If diagnosis is a known chronic condition and past history doesn't mention it, system shows a soft warning: "Diagnosis is COPD exacerbation but COPD not marked in past history – please verify"

Expected length of stay gets a smart suggestion based on diagnosis (e.g., pneumonia → 5-7 days, appendectomy → 3-4 days) that the user can override

Phase 6: Cost Estimation
What the user sees
A structured cost form with smart defaults based on the hospital's own rate card (pre-configured during setup):

Cost Head	Rate	Qty/Days	Total
Room rent	₹X/day	Y days	Auto-calculated
Nursing charges	₹X/day	Y days	Auto-calculated
ICU charges	₹X/day	Z days	Auto-calculated
OT charges	₹X	1	₹X
Surgeon fee	Manual	—	Manual
Anesthetist fee	Manual	—	Manual
Consultant fee	Manual	—	Manual
Investigations	Manual	—	Manual
Medicines	Manual	—	Manual
Consumables	Manual	—	Manual
Implants (if any)	Add rows	—	Sum
Ambulance	Manual	—	Manual
Misc	Manual	—	Manual
Running total updates live at the bottom

A "Amount claimed from insurer" field (defaults to total, user can reduce if patient pays a portion)

A coverage check: if total > sum insured, show a warning banner: "Estimated cost ₹X exceeds sum insured ₹Y by ₹Z – patient may need to pay the difference"

If the hospital uses package rates for certain procedures, a toggle: "Apply package rate?" with package name and flat amount

Phase 7: Document Upload & Evidence Linking
What the system shows
Two sections side by side:

Left: Required Documents Checklist (auto-generated based on diagnosis)

Clinical evidence: CBC, X-ray, ABG, ECG, etc. (based on ICD-10 mapping)

Administrative: Policy copy, ID proof, PAN (if cost > ₹1 lakh), admission letter

Each shows status: ✓ Uploaded, ⚠ Required – Missing, ○ Optional

Right: Upload Area

Drag-and-drop or camera capture

On upload, AI attempts to auto-classify the document (X-ray vs CBC vs ID proof) using filename + basic image/PDF analysis

User confirms or corrects the classification

If voice-captured findings exist (e.g., "X-ray shows consolidation"), the system auto-links the uploaded X-ray to that finding

Smart behavior
If a voice-captured finding says "CBC shows Hb 8.2" but no CBC report is uploaded, a prominent card appears: "You mentioned CBC results – upload the report to strengthen the claim"

Missing required documents show a count badge on the step indicator

User can mark any document as "Will submit later" – this flags the pre-auth as PENDING DOCUMENTS
​

Phase 8: Medical Necessity Auto-Generation
What happens behind the scenes
The system takes ALL the structured data collected so far and auto-generates a medical necessity statement that answers the three questions every TPA reviewer asks:

What is wrong with the patient? (diagnosis + clinical evidence)

Why does the patient need to be admitted? (severity + why OPD won't work)

What will you do and how much will it cost? (treatment plan + cost estimate)

What the user sees
A preview card showing the generated medical necessity narrative

An "Edit" button to refine wording (but most users should not need to)

A strength indicator: "Strong / Moderate / Weak" based on:

Whether all required documents are attached

Whether vitals support the severity claim

Whether diagnosis and findings are consistent

Whether cost estimate is within typical range for that diagnosis

Phase 9: Review & Declarations
What the user sees
A full summary page showing all 7 IRDAI sections in a compact, scannable layout:

Section 1-3: Patient + Policy + Hospital (collapsed, expandable)

Section 4: Clinical details (expanded, prominent)

Section 5: Admission details + past history

Section 6: Cost breakup with total

Section 7: Three declaration blocks

Declarations flow
Patient/Insured declaration: Checkbox + "Patient/attendant has been informed and consents" (insurance desk confirms verbally and ticks)

Doctor declaration: Shows doctor's name, qualification, registration number. If the doctor is logged in, they confirm with a tap/click. If not, system records "Pending doctor confirmation" and sends a push notification to the doctor's Aivana app for async confirmation.

Hospital declaration: Auto-filled with hospital's authorized signatory from system config. Checkbox for "Hospital seal will be applied on printed copy."

Phase 10: Generate & Submit
What happens when "Generate Pre-Auth" is clicked
System validates all mandatory fields; any missing fields scroll the user to the gap with a red highlight

Pre-auth document is generated in three formats simultaneously:

Structured digital format (JSON) for API submission to TPA portals

IRDAI Part-C formatted text for email/fax submission

PDF matching the standard Part-C layout for printing and physical submission with hospital seal

A unique Pre-Auth Reference ID is assigned (e.g., PA-AIVANA-20260303-0042)

Audit trail is locked: who filled what, when, which fields were auto-filled vs manually entered, which were overridden

What the user sees
A success screen with:

Reference ID prominently displayed

Three action buttons: "Submit to TPA Portal" (if API integration exists), "Download PDF", "Send via Email"

Document status badge: "✓ COMPLETE" or "⚠ PENDING DOCUMENTS (2 missing)"

A timeline preview: "Typical TPA response time for [TPA name]: 2-4 hours (planned) / 4-6 hours (emergency)"

Option to print directly for physical submission with seal and signature

Phase 11: Post-Submission Tracking
After submission, the pre-auth appears in the dashboard queue with live status:

Submitted → waiting for TPA response

Query Raised → TPA asked for clarification or additional documents; the system shows exactly what's needed and lets the user respond inline

Approved → shows approved amount, any deductions, co-pay noted

Denied → shows denial reason; system suggests corrective action (e.g., "Add medical necessity justification for ICU stay" or "Upload missing blood culture report")

Enhancement Requested → if actual costs exceed approved amount mid-treatment, a one-click "Request Enhancement" flow pre-fills the delta